column168: On June 9, 2016 A Seaboard Marine Equipment Operator was transporting the MEGC (WCGU000049-0) from the Vessel (National Glory) to the South yard. The MEGC was being transported on a chassis that was placed on top of a flat rack. These flat rack was placed on top of a bombcart for transport. When the operator crossed the West end railroad tracks, the cargo shifted due to one of the chassis legs penetrating the wood of the flat rack causing it to fall from the bombcart. The center of gravity for the cargo was too high (approx. 8 feet). Damages to the Cross Member and bracing supports on the cage that surrounds the MEGC were reported but no release. Fire Dept, Safety dept. and Security arrived at the scene within minutes in order to address the incident. Fire Dept. inspected the unit and advised that no release was present and that the product inside the MEGC was in good order. The Same day, Cargo was moved to final destination for removal of the product and repairs of the unit.

column168: AT APPROX. 3:35 A.M. ON 6/21/16, A LEAKING PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED SITTING IN A UPS TOTE BOX OUTSIDE ON THE GROUND BESIDE THE DMP STORAGE SHED AT THE CENTENNIAL HUB FACILITY. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION BY THE PRELOAD RMP   RESPONDERS THE PKG WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN A BROKEN GLASS JAR OF CHLOROFORM. UPON REVIEWING THE SHIPPING PAPERS IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE PACKAGE CONTAINED AN RQ AND PE WAS NOTIFIED AT APPROX. 3:45 A.M. UPON REVIEW OF THE QUANTITY OF THE SPILL AND THE RQ VALUES (CHLOROFORM HAS AN RQ OF 10 LBS - THE PACKAGE CONTAINED 1X4L CONTAINER = 12.6 LBS. RELEASED), THE PRELOAD RMP WAS DIRECTED TO CALL THE RELEASE INTO JEFFERSON COUNTY 911 AS REQUIRED BY THE LOCAL HMPC ORDINANCE. 911 WAS CONTACTED AT APPROX. 4:08 A.M.. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AT THE FACILITY TO REVIEW THE INCIDENT AT APPROX. 4:25 A.M. THE NRC AS WELL AS THE KY CABINET FOR ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION WERE ALSO CONTACTED TO REPORT THE RELEASE.

Norfolk Southern personnel reported a strong odor around tank car GATX66417.  Upon inspection by a contractor, the source of the odor was found to be vapors leaking from the manway.  The manway was pinched.  The contractor installed a nozzle gasket and secured the manway to correct the problem.
column169: The shipper needs to have their tank car manways inspected for defects and use nozzle gaskets instead of rim gaskets.

column168: ON THURSDAY JUNE 9TH 2016 AIRGAS ROY ROGELIO HUGHES WAS DRIVING AIRGAS TRUCK #303349 (2012 FORD F550 VIN#1FDUF5GT0CEA82912) FROM HIS LAST STOP IN EAGLE PASS TX AT 14:40 AND HEADING BACK TO THE AIRGAS DILLEY TX LOCATION. AS HE WAS DRIVING ON BUSINESS ROUTE HWY 227 SOUTH FROM EAGLE PASS TOWARDS CARRIZO SPRINGS TX APPROXIMATELY 10 MILES EAST OF EAGLE PASS THE TRUCK SUDDENTLY STARTED TO SHUT DOWN AND THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY NOTICED THE SMELL OF SMOKE COMING THROUGH THE VENTS OF THE TRUCK. THE AIRGAS DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PULLED OVER ONTO TEH SIDE OF THE ROAD OF BUSINESS ROUTE HWY 277 SOUTH AND TIRED TO USE THE TRUCK'S FIRE EXTINGUSHER TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE. HOWERVER HE WAS NOT ABLE TO AND HE CALLED 911. HE WAS DIRECTED TO MOVE AS FAR WAY FROM THE VEHICLE AS POSSIBE. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT , SHEIFF'S DEPARTMENT AND DPS ALL RESPONDED TO THE FIRE. THE FIRE WAS CONTAINED TO THE TRUCK AND IMMEDIATE AREA AROUND THE TRUCK. THE HIGHWAY WAS CLOSED FORM APPROXIMATELY 2 HOURS WHILE THE CREWS WORKED ON THE FIRE. THERE WERE TWO 2 EMPTY AA-2400 DOT CYLINDERS OF ELIUM COMPRESSED GAS (UN1046) ON THE TRUCK AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT AND THERE WAS NO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RELEASE FORM THE CYLINDERS
column169: WE ARE REVIEWING THE PREVENTATIVE MAINTENANCE PROCESS OF THE MAINTENANCE VENDOR THAT PERFORMED THE SERVICE WORK ON THE VEHICLE A WEEK PRIOR TO THE INCIDENT TO DETERMINE THE ROOT CAUSE AND IMPLEMENT CORRECTIVE ACTION AS NEEDED.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 20:00 A PACKAGE WAS BEING PROCEESED THROUGH THE PLEASANTDALE HUB FACILTIY ON A CONVERYOR BELT. THE HIGH VOLUME PICKOFF EMPLOYUEE NOTICED THAT A PACKAGE WAS SMOKING AND ON FIRE. HE NOTIFED HIS SUPERVIOSR WHO THEN REACHED OUT TO THE PE DEPARTEMENT. THE MECHANICS ARRIVED AN PUT THE FIRE OUT WITH A FIRE EXTINGUISHER. THE FIRE DAMAAGE 6 OTHER PACKAGES ON TEH BELT AND PORTIONS ALONG 15 OF THE BELT. THE BUILDING WAS EVACUATED FOR ABOUT 20 MINUTES AND THE SORT WAS BACK INTO SERVICE AROUND 20:20 PM. IT APPEARS THAT THE HAZ MAT PACKAGE WAS CAUGHT IN A JAM ON THE CONVEYOR. THE FRACTION FROM THE MOVING BELT OR STATIC CHANGES MAY HAVE IGNITED THE RESULTING FLAMMABLE VAPORS. NO ONE WAS INJURED DUE TO THIS INCIDENT

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED LEAKING AT DHL EXPRESS 236 WENDELL H FORD BLVD ERLANGER KY 41018 ON 6/15/2016 AT APPROXIMATELY 03:45. IT WAS REMOVED FROM THE AREA AND OPENED FOR INSPECTION. THE SHIPMENT WAS PREPARED AS DANGEROUS GOODS IN EXCEPTED QUANTITIES BECAUSE OF THE CLASS 3 IN THE PACKAGE. THE PEPPERMINT OIL THAT BROKE AND LEAKED MET THE CRITERIA FOR IATA SPECIAL PROVISION A 197 AND THE HAZ CLASS DID NOT HAVE TO BE MARKED ON THE EQ LABEL. ALTHOUGH THE PACKAGE CONTAINED AIR BUBBLE INNER CUSHIONING TO PROTECT THE CONTENTS DURING TRANSPORT, TI HAD NOT ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO ABSORB CONTENTS IN THE EVENT OF A LEAK. The container was isolated and the shipper, Schneider National Inc representative F. Abbott 973-331-1636 was notified by CSXI Customer Service. SUNPRO Services, CSXT  emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found one 300gal tote leaked 3gals of product due to package failure at seams. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. Contractor personnel secured the leak with absorbent materials, deconned contaminated areas, and cleaned up the material. The original freight container with proper load/block/brace was  released to the shipper.      This incident did not require a special switching move.  This incident did not require a Form 7.1..

column168: On 06/20/2016 at 1415hrs personnel with CSX Intermodal Bedford Park IL Terminal discovered SIMU259425, a loaded container of UN1289, Sodium Methylate Solution, 3(8), III, a 20ft portable tank leaked approximately 10lbs of liquid from flange valve area onto tank and asphalt pavement. The portable tank was isolated and Chemtrec report#20160620-00155, NRC report#1151141, ILL EMA report#H2016-0539 were notified. The rail shipper, CMA_CGM representative Phyllis Hoffman 757-961-2300 was notified by CSXI Customer Service. SUNPRO Services, CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found 10lbs liquid product released due to the nuts loose on the flange. The issue was identified and corrective actions were  communicated to the shipper. Contractor personnel secured the leak with tightening of the nuts on the flange, deconned spilled areas, and cleaned up the material. The original 20ft portable tank was released to the shipper.    This incident did not require a special switching move.  This incident did not require a Form 7.1.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: On June 22, 2016 at 11:00 hours personnel in the CSXT Avon Yard discovered UTLX 957652, a residue tank car of Petroleum Gases, Liquefied, leaking from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Targa Transport, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report 2016-06-22-00150).  Environmental Management Specialists (EMS), a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found product leaking from a vapor line valve that was not in closed position and secondary securement plug less than tool tight.  EMS also noted that both liquid line valves were not fully in the closed position and the secondary securement plugs were less than tool tight. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative (David Lindow 713-584-1448).  All valves were closed and the secondary securement plugs installed wrench tight.  The car was released for transportation.  No Special switching move was required.    NARRI: 5(4+5+0) x (2+0) = 90  Cause Code: 134  .
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On June 23, 2016 at 16:54 hours personnel in the CSXT Avon Yard reported that an FRA inspector had found UTLX 68242 a loaded tank car of Toxic Liquid, Inorganic, N.O.S. (Sodium Nitrate), leaking from the bottom of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Chemtrade Chemicals, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report 2016-06-23-00278).  Environmental Management Specialists, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found product had released from the bottom outlet valve operating stems packing gland nut.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative (Rick Bullis 409-767-4048).  The bottom outlet valve operating stems packing nut was tightened which secured the release.  The car was held at Avon, IN pending the shipper obtaining a One Time Movement Approval from the FRA.     NARRI: 2(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 32  Cause Code: 547

column168: This incident pertains to a release of UN1593 Methylene Chloride (6.1), PG III. Approximately 40 gallons of material released from (1) - 55 gallon steel drum due to a forklift puncture during loading operations. The release impacted a portion of the dock floor. The damaged drum was over packed and staged at this location pending the shippers disposition instructions. All generated wastes were staged on site pending profiling and disposal.

An environmental service contractor was dispatched and the release was cleaned up in accordance with regulations.

column168: On June 30, 2016,  XPO Logistics (XSL Terminal) notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous UN1824 Lab Solutions Liquid Detergent (PRO#632664874) release. According to Mr. Medley a 10 pound fiberboard box was damaged due to a load shift and was staged on the dock. Approximately 1 quart of product was released to the box and a 1' x 1' area of the dock. 0320 ERTS reviewed the SDS and instructed terminal personnel to use gloves eye protection and diluted absorbents to clean the release. Terminal personnel will place the damaged box and impacted absorbents into a 55 gallon poly drum in OS & D.

column168: A 55 gallon steel drum of UN2735 Rhino Extreme Resin Black was punctured by a fork lift blade while unloading a trailer at the R&L Carriers Terminal in Houston, Texas.  The damaged drum released approximately 50 gallons of product to the trailer floor and parking lot.  No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the release.  the release was cleaned with granular absorbents and the damaged drum over packed. All the waste was taken offsite to be disposed of in accordance with applicable laws.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: On June 24, 2016 at 2300 ET, a 5-gallon metal pail was punctured by a fork-lift blade which resulted in a release of approximately 2.5 gallons to the trailer floor. A contractor was dispatched for cleanup. Granular absorbents were worked in to the trailer floor thoroughly. The pail suffered too much damage to salvage, so it was combined with the cleanup debris and impacted absorbents into a 55-gallon steel drum for waste. The drum was staged on site for XPO Logistics to manage.
column172: Metal pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: WHILE UNLOADING THE TRAILER, ONE DRUM WAS FOUND ON ITS SIDE PUNCTURED AND LEAKING. THE RELEASE WAS PROPERLY MANAGED. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND HELD PENDING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.
column169: ALWAYS SECURE TO PREVENT MOVEMENT.

column168: AT 9:35 JUNE 17TH, 2016 UPS DRIVER JACOB STYRCZULA WAS ON HIS WAY TO MAKE A DELIVERY WHEN HE NOTICED SMOKE COMING FROM UNDER THE BULK HEAD DOOR. DRIVER STYRCZULA IMMEDIATELY PULLED HIS VEHICLE ONTO THE NEAREST SIDE STREET AND STOPPED AT 2901 MAPLE ST. BERWYN, IL. 60402. DRIVER STYRCZULA GOT OUT OF HIS VEHICLE AND NOTICED SMOKE COMING OUT OF THE ROOF AND SIDES OF HIS TRUCK. THE DRIVER THEN CALLED 911 EMERGENCY RESPONSES. THE CITY OF BERWYN ILLINOIS DISPATCHED THEIR POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENTS TO THE SCENE. UPON ARRIVING AT THE SCENE, BERWYN FIRE DEPARTMENT FIRST LIEUTENANT, JERRY MARZULLO, OPENED THE REAR DOOR OF THE VEHICLE AND FOUND A LARGE BOX WITH A LAWNMOWER AND SEVERAL NEARBY PACKAGES ON FIRE. THIS PACKAGE ALSO CONTAINED A SEALED LEAD ACID BATTERY WITH NO PROTECTION ON THE TERMINALS TO PREVENT ACCIDENTAL ARCING. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT IMMEDIATELY PULLED OUT THEIR HOSES AND STARTED DOUSING THE FIRE AND OTHER PACKAGES IN THE VEHICLE. ONCE THE FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED, FIRST LIEUTENANT MARZULLO DETERMINED THAT THE LAWNMOWER WAS BEING SHIPPED WITH SOME TYPE OF COMBUSTIBLE FLUID. HE ALSO DETERMINED THAT THIS LAWNMOWER WAS THE CAUSE OF THE FIRE BECAUSE THE MAJORITY OF THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED IN THE LOCATION OF WHERE THE LAWNMOWER WAS PLACED IN THE VEHICLE.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column58: Bottom Outlet Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve
column62: Inadequate Preparation for Transportation; Valve Open
column168: 6/7/2016: At approximately 1900 hours, Train-master D. Robertson reported tank car DOWX 4282, load N-Propanol, was leaking from the bottom outlet, in a steady drip, while at CR's Port Reading, NJ yard.    CR emergency response contractor Hepaco was contacted and inspected the tank car, noting the release from the bottom outlet due to the top operated bottom outlet valve not fully closed (requiring 3 full turns, stopping the leak); the top operating rod's packing gland nut was not tool tight (secured during the inspection); and, the bottom outlet 4" closure cap was missing a gasket (replaced in kind during the inspection).    No environmental clean up required as product dissipated and evaporated rapidly.  Car secured and okayed for delivery to original destination.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Driver was traveling south on Tennessee state highway 243. As driver was approaching intersection of TN Hwy 243 and US Highway 43 north, driver stated he heard a loud POP. Driver looked in his left mirror and saw the "hot pot", molten container, falling off the trailer. Driver attempted to turn the truck, and apply brakes to upright the container. This did not work. The container of molten aluminum , along with the tractor and trailer overturned causing spillage of molten aluminum. The POP was believed to be one of the binders that secured the "hot pot" to the trailer breaking free from the trailer. The lid to the hot pot then broke free allowing the molten aluminum to spill on to the roadway and into the grass.  The spill was contained and cleaned up within 4 hours. The roadway required repairs that were completed the following day.     The trailer has been modified for a different type binder, as well as having the lids of the hot pots engineered in a different manner.
column169: The drivers that transport these types of loads have been retrained on speed while coming into curves. The shipper has since redesigned the binders as well as the lid  being engineered in a new manner.

column168: 2 employees where using 12412 to pump bleach into a basement storage tank at a pool.  One employee was at the tank and another in the truck.  The employee in the truck placed the pump into a tote of hydrochloric acid and turned on the pump.  He immediately realized his error and shut down the pump and alerted the employee at the other end of the hose to close a valve to prevent product entering tank due to gravity.  Employee at tank closed the valve, but not before a cup of acid entered appox 100 gals of bleach in the storage tank.  Employee smelled chlorine being release from the bleach and evacuated the facility and called for Columbia FD to determine if area was safe to enter.  Columbia FD responded and entered the space and found no chlorine in the room.  Amount of acid entering the tank would not cause a RQ release of chlorine.  Hawkins employees at the direction of the fire department used the bleach to super chlorinate the pool.
column169: Employee reminded to verify product before engaging pump.  Also directing employees that one employee must be in charge of operations such as these and hsa to verify everything before beginning unloading

column168: During unloading operations one poly pail containing UN1263 paint was discovered to had been punctured via a broken pallet resulting in approximately 3 liquid gallons of material to be released to the trailer floor. The drum containing the impacted absorbents were taken offsite for disposal by the contractor while the drum containing the damaged pail was left onsite pending disposition. No drains, soils, or waterways were impacted.

It was reported that an improperly loaded case of 4 plastic jugs was found  leaking inside the trailer. 2 of the plastic jugs are fine but the other two were  damaged and leaked approximately 2 gallons of product. Terminal Personnel  state that another case of jugs is pinched between the trailer wall and load rack  and that it does not appear to be leaking at this time but could be leaking inside  the case. No drains, soils, or waterways were impacted. The 2 damaged jugs are being transported off site as salvage to minimize disposal costs. The cleanup debris will be disposed of as nonhazardous. 1-55 gallon drum of waste was generated from the cleanup.

The pail had apparently been punctured by a fork lift blade while loading at the previous terminal.  The damaged pail released approximately 2.5 gallons of product to the trailer floor. column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: On June 24, 2016 at 0705 ET, during unloading operations, the terminal personnel found a (1) 55-gallon poly drum leaking UN18124 Car Wash Soap "Optima Premium Pre-soak" due to a nail puncture from the underlying pallet. Approximately 2 gallons had released to the trailer floor. A contractor was dispatched who contained, cleaned, and neutralized the release. The damaged drum was overpacked into a (1) 95-gallon poly overpack which was labeled as salvageable material and staged onsite for the terminal to manage. A (1) 30-gallon poly drum containing the neutralized absorbents labeled as non-haz waste was also staged onsite for the terminal to manage.

A 300 gallon steel tote of UN1993 Unisol Liquid Red arrived at the XPO Logistics terminal in Jacksonville, FL leaking from its top closure.  The top closure had a damaged seal that allowed approximately 1 pint of material to be released during transit due to sloshing of the  materiel.  The release impacted the body of the tote and no soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the release and re-secure the lid top.  The shipper of the tote provided a new lid seal.  The seal was replaced and the tote tested.  The release stopped once the tote lid was re-secured with the new seal.  The sides of the tote were wiped clean and all waste generated was left at the terminal for XPO personnel to manage.

A 275 gallon composite tote of UN1760 Eucon WO arrived leaking at the XPO Logistics terminal in Tomah, WI.  The tote released approximately 10 gallons of product to the trailer floor through an improperly secured top cap during transit.  No soils, drains or waterways were impacted.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the release and re-secure the cap.  The contractors re-secured the cap and tested the tote to ensure the release had stopped.  The trailer floor was neutralized and cleaned.   The tote was cleaned and continued on for shipping. All generated waste was left on site for XPO personnel to manage.

On June 9, 2016 the driver of a Liquid Transport tractor trailer discovered that their DOT407 trailer had a slow leak from the bottom.  The tanker trailer was carrying UN1105 Amyl Alcohol.  This was discovered at a rest stop along I 65 near mile marker 83 in Castleberry, AL.  The driver stated that the leak was a steady drip coming from under the jacket of the insulation approximately 6 feet from the belly valve and running backwards.  The driver placed a bucket underneath the drip which collected approximately 2 cups of material.  No soils, drains or waterways were impacted.  It is unknown how the leak in the trailer formed as there was no apparent damaged to the body of the trailer.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to supervise a Liquid Transport crew transfer the product into a new relief tanker.  The trailers were properly grounded and bonded along with transfer pumps equipment.  The transfer was successfully performed without incident and the leaking, now empty, trailer taken for inspection/repairs.  The newly filled trailer was taken back to the shipper for product testing.

It was reported that the driver noticed approx. 1 gallon of product released from the nose of the trailer and onto the concrete of the parking lot. Contractor found a skid containing (7) poly jerricans. (3) 25 liter jerricans released UN1219 to the floor of the trailer.

column168: At the R&L Carriers terminal in Phoenix, AZ a pallet containing 5 gallon pails of UN1719 X-33 Break Preasoak arrived damaged and leaking. The damaged pail was over packed into a poly drum and properly labeled as salvage. The over pack drum remained on site for R&L personnel to manage.

column168: On June 29, 2016, the rear brakes of a Schneider Bulk Carriers DOT407 trailer caught fire due to an unknown mechanical error. The trailer was carrying UN3082 MIN T75U5, a scale inhibitor.  The fire damaged the 2 valve assemblies on the bottom of the trailer.  There was no release of any material, no road closures, and no injuries. Due to the fire the tractor was inoperable.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to trans load the material into a new relief trailer.  The material was removed from the damaged tanker via the top hatch and loaded into the relief trailer through the bottom valves. The transfer was completed without incident or any release of material.  Due to the fire the bottom valve assemblies were damaged and subsequently replaced.

A vehicle operated by Safety Kleen Systems, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the transfer operation, it was discovered that approximately 2 ounces of material had  escaped from a pinhole leak that had developed in the container. Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised  container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and  placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity. IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and have been asked to inspect all container used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required  specifications.

column168: There was no package failure.  Consignee's storage tank overflowed while the carrier was unloading the CTMV.  The carrier immediately stopped unloading, however, the storage tank continued to overflow.  Released hazmat was contained in the consignee's storage tank containment structure, mitigating the impact of the release.      Investigation revealed that the CTMV was connected to the wrong consignee pipeline.  The unloading area has two nearly identical, unmarked pipes that lead to two different product storage tanks.  The heats of solution and neutralization of the resultant mixture appears to have caused the storage tank to boil over for about two hours.    Our reference: E60723

The consignee advised our driver that the gasket in their hose was faulty and they were replacing it with a new one. column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 2021 ON 06/06/2016, BNSF WAS NOTIFIED BY YARD PERSONNEL THAT THE GATX7934 WAS ACTIVELY LEAKING WHILE IN AN INBOUND TACK. THE CAR HAD BEEN STATIONARY ON THE 6TH AND THE LEAK WAS ESTIMATED AT <40 GALLON BASED UPON OBSERVATION BY YARD PERSONNEL. THE AREA WAS ISOLATED AROUND THE CAR AND BNSF HAZMAT PERSONNEL RESPONDED TO THE YARD TO INSPECT THE CAR. IT WAS FOUND THAT LIQUID HAD LEAKED FROM BOTH THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVES  (PRV’S) ON THE CAR, THE PRV’S WERE INTACT AND FUNCTIONING AS INTENDED. THE CAR WAS DETERMINED TO BE OVERLOADED BY VOLUME, THE HEAT DURING THE DAY EXPANDING THE LIQUID AND FORCING IT THOUGHT THE PRV’S. A HAZMAT CONTRACT WAS DISPATCHED TO REDUCE THE CAR SO AS TO ALLOW FOR PROPER VAPOR SPACE ALLOWANCE IN THE CAR. THE CAR WAS SWITCHED TO REPAIR AND INSPECTION TRACK FOR THE REEDUCATION APPROXIMATELY 500 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WAS REMOVED FROM THE CAR AND STORED IN TWO 275 G TOTES FOR PROPER HANDING BY THE SHIPPER. THE IMPACTED SOILS WERE REMOVED TO CLEAN SOIL AND REPLACED WITH NEW BALLAST. RELEASE VOLUMES ARE THE BEST ESTIMATIONS BASED UPON INFORMATION RECEIVED FROM THE FIELD AND OBSERVATIONS
column169: SHIPPER HAD BEEN NOTIFIED OF THE ISSUE. THE SHIPPER SHOULD REVIEW ALL LOADING PRACTICES TO ENSURE THAT PROPER PROCEDURES ARE IN PLACE TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.

column168: AS DRIVER HAD JUST ARRIVE TO MAKE HIS DELIVER AND WAS PREPARING TO GET SET UP, THE OPERATOR NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE DRAIN HOSE COMING FROM THE CRASH BOX AND A SMALL TRIAL OF PRODUCT ABOUT 1 INCH WIDE LEADING INTO THE UNLOADING AREA. AFTER INVESTIGATING FURTHER IT WAS FOUND THAT THE DOME LID HAD NOT BEEN SECURELY FASTENED ALL THE WAY AROUND ALLOWING SOME PRODUCT TO LEAK OUT. THE DOME ANCHOR BOLTS WERE ALL CHECKED AND SECURELY FASTENED AND PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP. IN GOOD FAITH A HAZ MAT COMPANY (SWS) WAS CALLED OUT TO CHECK FOR ANY PRODUCT THAT MAY HAVE LEAKED ONTO THE ROADWAY EN-ROUTE TO THE DRIVERS DESTINATION. AFTER DRIVING FOR SEVERAL MILES IT APPEARED THAT THERE WERE A FEW WET SPOTS BUT NOT A STEADY STREAM ON THE ROADWAY WHICH MAY HAVE HAD SOME TYPE OF LIQUID ON IT BUT WAS NOT SURE IF IT CAME FROM OUR TRAILER OR WHAT IT WAS AS HEAVY TRAFFIC HAD BEEN DRIVING ON IT. SWS ALSO TOOK POSSESSION OF AN ACCUMULATED DRUM OF SOLIDIFIED WASTE WITH THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL FOR THE MATERIAL THAT HAD DRIPPED ONTO THE GROUND AND WAS CLEANUP . WE DID NOT RECEIVE ANY CALLS FROM MOTORIST WHO MAY HAVE COME IN CONTACT WITH THE PRODUCT THEREFORE WE ARE UNCERTAIN AS TO WHEN THE WING NUT COME LOOSE DURING TRANSIT CAUSING LEAKAGE.
column169: DRIVER HAS BEEN RE-TRAINED ON CONDUCTING A PROPER PRE-TRIP INSPECTION AS REQUIRED WHICH INCLUDES A HANDS ON VERIFICATION THAT THE DOME [IS SECURED AND ALL WING NUTS ARE FASTENED TIGHTLY AND NOT JUST ASSUME THAT A PRE-LOADED TRAILER HAS BEEN CAREFULLY INSPECTED AND IS ROAD READY. CONDUCTING A THOROUGH PRE -TRIP INSPECTION IS A MANDATORY REQUIREMENT ON ANY TRAILER THE DRIVER CONNECTS TO AND IS VERIFIED WITH HIS SIGNATURE.

MORNING OF 07/01/2016, EPS (THREE MAN CREW, SECOND CONTACT GREG TAX SENT OVER WORK AUTHORIZATION AND CREDIT AUTHORIZATION) ARRIVED ON-SITE AT 0630-ISH. THE LEAKING CONTAINER WAS IDENTIFIED AS A FIVE TO SEVEN GALLON PLASTIC CARBOY WITH A 2'' AND 1/2'' BUNG. PLEASE REFER TO PICTURES. LEL LEVELS INSIDE THE VAN UPON ENTRY WERE 1000 TO 2000 PPM AND QUICKLY DISSIPATED ONCE THE LIQUID WAS CLEANED UP FROM THE INSIDE OF THE VAN. CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED BY 0755. THE CONTAINER APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN LOADED HIGH UP IN THE VAN AND FELL TO THE TOP OF A STEEL DRUM. WHEN IT FELL, THE CONTAINER REMAINED INTACT. HOWEVER, THE SMALL VENT CAP WAS NOT TIGHT AND LIQUID LEAKED FROM THE VENT HOLE. THE CONTAINER DID NOT NEED TO BE OVER PACKED, THE BUNGS WERE SIMPLY TIGHTENED. ABOUT 1.5 GALLONS OF LIQUID ACCUMULATED ON TOP OF TWO STEEL DRUMS THEN THE LIQUID BEGAN TO FALL ON THE VAN FLOOR, VAN TIRE, ETC. THE FREE LIQUID WAS CLEANED UP/ABSORBED; THE PPE, ABSORBENT AND OTHER DEBRIS WERE CONTAINERIZED, A SHIPPING PAPER (BOL) CREATED, THE DEBRIS DRUM LOADED ONTO THE VAN.   THE CONTRACTOR INDICATED THAT THE LOAD WAS POORLY LOADED, PAILS WERE ON PALLETS WITH SHRINK WRAP THAT WAS NOT TIGHT, SUCH A VARIETY OF CONTAINER SIZES AND TYPES WERE LOADED AND NOT PROPERLY SECURED. DRIVER WAS ON THE ROAD BY 0845.

column168: DRIVER WAS DELIVERING 1780 GALLONS OF 93 OCTANE PREMIUM FUEL TO PONTOTOC, MS LOCATION. DRIVER PULLED VEEDER ROOT PRIOR TO STARTING DELIVERY WHERE IT READ 90% ULLAGE OF 1735 GALLONS. DRIVER STATES APPROXIMATELY 4 MINUTES INTO THE DELIVERY FUEL STARTED TO RISE OUT OF THE DROP TUBE AND FLOWING OUT OF THE CONNECTION BETWEEN THE DROP TUBE AND HOSE FITTING. THE FLOW WAS IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF FROM THE CARGO TANK TO THE IN-GROUND STORE TANK. FUEL FLOW DID NOT STOP UNTIL APPROXIMATELY 68 GALLONS WAS RELEASED ONTO THE STORE PARKING LOT. DUE TO THE ANGLE OF THE STORE PARKING LOT FUEL FLOWED INTO HWY 15 AND BEHIND THE LOCAL MCDONALDS. THE APPROXIMATE GALLONS LOST WAS CALCULATED WHERE AS THE GALLONS. THE CARGO TANK COMPARTMENT WAS LOADED WITH 1780 NET GALLONS AND CONTAINED 11 INCHES OF FUEL INSIDE THE COMPARTMENT AFTER THE DELIVERY WAS STOPPED EQUIVALENT TO 248 GALLONS. TOTAL RELEASE APPROX. 68 GALLONS. FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED FOR ASSISTANCE IN CLEAN UP. HWY 15 WAS BLOCKED DUE TO FUEL ENTERING ROADWAY UNTIL IT WAS CLEANED UP. PONTOTOC COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY (PCEMA) REPORTED TO THE INCIDENT AS WELL' WHEREAS, IT WAS REPORTED THE MCDONALD'S EMPLOYEES EVACUATED DUE TO THE SMELL OF FUMES AND RETURNED TO WORK AFTER CLEAN UP. EVACUATION HEAD COUNT OR TIME WAS NOT CALCULATED. USES WAS CONTACTED BY PONTOTOC COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY FOR REMEDIATION TO THE SITE. AT THIS POINT WE HAVE NOT RECEIVED ANY INFORMATION OR REPORT USES. PCEMA STATED FUEL ENTERED STORM DRAIN; HOWEVER, NO AMOUNT WAS DETERMINED. MDEQ WAS CONTACTED BY PCEMA. A REPORT NUMBER IS NOT AVAILABLE.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, TWO 50LB BAGS WERE DISCOVERED DAMAGED INSIDE TRAILER. AREA WAS SECURED AND MSDS WAS CONSULTED. YOUNG'S ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. UPON INSPECTION, APPROXIMATELY 10 POUNDS OF DRY PRODUCT WERE DISCOVERED ON TRAILER FLOOR. FREE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED TO TRAILER FLOOR, AND DID NOT IMPACT GROUND SURFACE OR THREATEN TO IMPACT STATE WATERS. YOUNG'S ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP SWEPT UP THE DRIED PRODUCT, WHICH WAS CONTAINERIZED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM, ALONG WITH DAMAGED BAGS AND DEBRIS, PENDING DISPOSAL IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. REMAINING SHIPMENT WAS RESHRINKWRAPPED, LOADED, AND SENT ON TO ITS DESTINATION. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.
column169: ROADRUNNER TRANSPORTATION SERVICES WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND REINFORCE SAFE HANDLING PROCEDURES AND DRIVER SAFETY TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column42: AMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S. OR POLYAMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S.
column168: Liquid was noted leaking from trailer RDWY122753 onto the deck of flat car TTRX360817 and onto ground. The trailer was removed from the flat car and transported to the HazMat containment pit. The flat car and ground contamination were cleaned up by an environmental contractor. The trailer was opened up to reveal a shipment that shifted during transport, resulting in one cracked 5-gallon bucket of epoxy. The cargo was removed and the spilled product was cleaned up by an environmental contractor.
column169: Shipper needs to ensure that they follow the proper packing procedures for loading product into trailers. Proper securement is also necessary to prevent shifting of product and eliminate the release of hazardous materials.

column168: Report of tank car IAPX 1030 leaking in the Tucson yard. Inspection showed the Liquid Level Gauge line was broken at the gauge. Repairs were made and shipper working on OTMA to continue the car in transportation.
column169: No additional comments.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: During loading procedures at the original terminal, a drum was discovered damaged inside the trailer. Further investigation revealed that the drum was punctured by a piece of freight that was loaded in front of it. The drum was immediately placed into an overpack along with the absorbents used to clean up the released material. Due to the hazard of material the package specifications were not able to be obtained.
column169: This incident may have been prevented had the proper dunnage been placed around the drums. This incident may be used in future dock meetings or training exercises to display the importance of dunnage and following proper loading procedures.

column168: While loading freight into trailer forklift operator struck the IBC that was already staged in the trailer with the freight he was loading into the trailer consequently puncturing the IBC contributing to the unintentional release. Spilled material was neutralized and cleaned with absorbent material and placed into a recovery container and punctured IBC was repaired with plastic putty and held for further disposition.
column169: Forklift operators and material handlers need to pay attention to their clearances including those of their freight to help prevent these types of unintentional releases from occurring.

column168: While unloading freight from trailer the stretch wrap wrapping around a pallet of cylinders got caught on a load bar while it was being removed from the trailer. As a result this made a cylinder that was staged on the pallet to fall off of the pallet and hit the floor which consequently caused the cylinder to leak from an unknown area. The cylinder was taken to a clear open area and allowed to vent until all contents vaporized out of the container.
column169: Try to keep an eye for these types of situations while unloading freight to help prevent these typres of events from occurring.

column42: ENGINES INTERNAL COMBUSTION, OR ENGINES, FUEL CELL, FLAMMABLE LIQUID POWERED
column168: On 6/20/16 at approximately 12:20pm, we received a satellite phone call from the Corvus crew on flight 931 that just departed bethel 20 minutes prior reporting that they smelled gas fumes inside the cabin. There was one piece of hazmat which was an outboard boat motor. They said they are returning to Bethel to investigate the issue. Upon landing we confirmed that the 2 stroke fuel/oil mix was leaked into the plane and there was a small puddle. After removing the motor and cleaning the fuel residue, it was determined by the crew and AC mechanics that some fuel had leaked into the lower floor boards because the fumes were still present. The proper paperwork had been filled out and there were no odors coming from the unit at the time it was received. According to the crew, There was also no odors or leaks discovered before departure, either. The change in pressure and or flight attitude probably caused the remaining fuel inside to evacuate the motor.    Report sent to company safety department and all internal combustion engine transportation was halted pending a complete investigation and a safety risk assessment completed.
column169: Revision to cargo acceptance training emphasizing fuel lines completely drained, sufficiently cleaned of residue and purged of vapors.

column168: On 06/25/16 at 1638 hours it was reported at Goulding Yard (CSXT), located in Pensacola, FL, that tank car SHPX201561, a loaded tank car of HEXAMETHYLENEDIAMINE SOLUTION, may be leaking.  The CSXT yardmaster received a voicemail message on the yard office line from the shipper, Ascend Performance Materials, that this car was mistakenly offered for transportation and released from their plant.  Ascend advised via a voicemail message to CSXT which was received at 1638 hours that the listed tank car had a leaking valve and was offered by mistake of Ascend to CSXT and that the waybill reflected a residue but the car was a load.  CSXT Hazmat Manager Trent Page responded to the yard and attempted contact back with Ascend with the return number left on the voicemail multiple times with no response back.  H/M Trent Page inspected the car and found a valve failure between the top and bottom flange assembly on the liquid line valve.  Product had escaped at this connection and had already solidified upon inspection with no leaks observed.  H/M Trent Page contacted the shipper, Ascend Performance Materials (Ed Waldynski 850-712-5036) via Chemtrec.  Ed, shipper Ascend Performance Materials, was updated and requested to confirm load status, update waybill, confirm known issues with the car, and dispatch a certified mobile repair company for valve repairs.  Ed confirmed that the car had a known valve failure at the plant and was mistakenly offered for transportation.    Ascend Performance Materials, shipper, updated the waybill to reflect a loaded car and dispatched ResCar who replaced a bad gasket on the liquid line flange connection.  Hepaco, CSX Emergency Response Contractor, responded and cleaned the housing and valve of released product.  The car will remain on hold status until an OTMA-1 is applied for by the shipper, Ascend, to move back to their facility for a pressure test.      Due to lack of evidence it was unable to be determined if any release occurred during transportation or prior to transportation.    NAR Code: 293 (5 pts) Connection between pipe flange liquid line valve; gasket deteriorated     5(5+3+5) x (2+0) = 130 NARRI         Pensacola, FL  06/25/16  SHPX201561  HEXAMETHYLENEDIAMINE SOLUTION
column169: Shipper must ensure proper inspections of their cars prior to offering for transportation.  Shipper must ensure load status and proper way billing prior to offering for transportation.

column168: On June 29, 2016 at 09:25 hours, personnel at CSXT Stanley Yard discovered UTLX 70402, a loaded UN 3257, Elevated Temperature Liquid, N.O.S. (Asphalt Flux) tank car to have wetness on the sides of the car coming from the top fitting protective area. The car was isolated and Safety Clean was notified via their emergency contact number (800-483-3718), and the shipper of record, Delray Connecting Railroad Co was contacted.  A CSX Emergency Response contractor, Sunpro was dispatched to the scene. Upon inspection it was determined that 6 of the manway bolts were less than tool tight.  They inspected the manway gasket and found no issues with the gasket.  As a preventative measure each of the bolts were tightened to the appropriate torque.     Cause Code: 200 at 5 points  NARRI: 5 (5 + 1 + 0) x (2 + 0) = 60

column168: THE SHIPMENT: WAS FOUND LEAKING IN THE SORT. UPON OPENING THE BOX WE FOUND SIX PLASTIC BOTTLES, ONE BOTTLE WITH A LOOSE CAP THAT ALLOWED THE SPILL TO OCCUR. I NOTIFIED FAA SA WAYNE KNIGHT WITH THE MEM SECFO ELECTRONICALLY. THE FREIGHT WAS HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.

column168: On 6/27/16 at approximately 0145 PT local switch crews in the interchange yard at Pittsburg, CA noticed LTCX 1924 a loaded cryogenic car filled with liquid argon leaking from the control cabinet on the side of the car.  Responding BNSF field officers and hazmat responder found a liquid leak coming from the liquid valve and evaporating upon contact with the ground.  The cause of the leak was primarily caused by failure of shipper to apply secondary closure cap on the liquid outlet.  Cap was found in the cabinet lying adjacent to the outlet.  The securement device holding the wheel valve for the liquid line in place for transportation became disengaged in transport due to a spoke on the wheel valve where it was connected had broken.  This allowed the valve to vibrate open, and lack of secondary closure cap allowed liquid to leak into the environment.  Outlet cap was applied by BNSF personnel, valve handle closed, and securement device re-attached.  No environmental cleanup required, car was allowed to proceed to local destination for offloading.
column169: Shipper must audit for compliance with DOT hazmat transportation rules and bring deficiencies into compliance during pre-trip inspection process.  This was deemed to be human factor and preventable non-accident caused release.

column168: EVENT/CLAIM #60798-1  DRIVER HAD LOADED THE PRODUCT AND CONDUCTED HIS PRE-TRIP INSPECTION.  AT THE TIME OF THAT INSPECTION, THE REAR WASH OUT CAP WAS IN PLACE. HE CONDUCTED A SLOSH TEST BY PRESSING HARD ON THE BRAKES AND NO PRODUCT WAS LEAKING AT THAT TIME.  HE DROVE A SHORT DISTANCE AND CAME TO A STOP SIGN.  WHEN HE STOPPED AT THE STOP SIGN, HE NOTICED THE PRODUCT LEAKING. THE DRIVER PULLED OVER AND SAW THAT THE REAR WASH CAP WAS NOW MISSING. THE WASH CAP WAS NOT FOUND.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED

column168: WHILE LOADING CRUDE OIL AT HPD FACILITY (17754 COUNTRY ROAD 32, PLATTEVILLE CO 80651) (LATITUDE 40.2.1683/ LONGITUDE 104.71985) AN ESTIMATED 2 BBLS (84 GALLONS) OF CRUDE OIL OVERFLOWED THE TRAILER. INITIALLY THERE WAS SOME QUESTION AS TO WHETHER THE TANK GAUGES WERE WORKING PROPERLY. SUBSEQUENT TO THE SPILL EVENT IT WAS DETERMINED THAT WHILE THE DRIVER WAS NOT PROPERLY KEEPING TRACK OF THE VOLUME LEVELS WITHIN EACH COMPARTMENT OF THE TRAILER. CONSEQUENTLY WHILE THE VOLUME BEING LOADED WAS WITHIN THE OVERALL TRAILER CAPACITY; IT EXCEEDED THE VOLUME AVAILABLE IN THE INDIVIDUAL COMPARTMENT BEING LOADED.     UPON RECOGNIZING THE RELEASE, THE DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE LOADING EQUIPMENT AND CLOSE THE VALVES TO THE TRAILER. HE THEN NOTIFIED FACILITY PERSONNEL AND RMCO EMERGENCY RESPONSE NETWORK. THE SPILLED OIL WAS CLEANED FOR THE LOADING AREA AROUND THE TRAILER AND THE TRAILER ITSELF. STAINED GRAVEL IN THE AREA WAS REMOVED. THE SPILL DID NOT LEAVE THE IMMEDIATE ARA BESIDE THE TRAILER, AND NO WATERWAYS WERE THREATENED OR IMPACTED. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR FIRE RELATED TO THIS RELEASE EVENT.
column169: FOLLOWING THE IMMEDIATE CLEANUP OF THE RELEASE; THE LOADED CRUDE OIL WAS TAKEN TO ITS INTENDED DESTINATION AND UNLOADED WITHOUT INCIDENT. THE DRIVER THEN TOOK THE TRUCK TO A RMCO SERVICE FACILITY TO VERIFY THAT THE GAUGING SYSTEM ON THE TRAILER WAS IN PROPER WORKING ORDER. FOLLOWING A REVIEW OF THE INCIDENT, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE DRIVER HAD NOT BEEN PROPERLY FOLLOWING RMCO POLICIES / PROCEDURES WHICH RESULTED IN THE SPILL EVENT. THE DRIVER'S EMPLOYMENT WITH RMCO WAS TERMINATED. RMCO IS REMINDING ITS DRIVERS OF THE IMPORTANCE TO ADHERE TO RMCO POLICES / PROCEDURES.

column168: THIS SPILL WAS CAUSED BY HUMAN ERROR. OUR DRIVER MADE AN ERROR ENTERING THE GALLONS THAN THE COMPARTMENT WOULD HOLD. WHEN THE PRODUCT HIT THE TOP PROBE, THE RACK SHUT DOWN BUT THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE WAS OPENED FOR A MOMENT AND SOME GAS SPRAYED INTO THE AIR. THE REMAINING GAS WAS SPILLED WHEN THE DRIVER REMOVED THE VAPOR RECOVERY LINE FROM THE TRAILER WITHOUT REALIZING THAT GAS HAD FILLED THE VAPOR LINE. ALL THE GAS THAT WAS SPILLED WENT INTO THE SPILL CONTAINMENT BASIN UNDER THE TRAILER. ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCTS SERVICES COMPANY WAS CALLED AND THEY VACUUMED OUT THE WATER AND GAS THAT WAS IN THE CONTAINMENT BASIN. CLAY ABSORBENTS WERE USED TO CLEAN THE CONCRETE UNDER THE TRAILER. THE NYS DEPT OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONVERSATION WAS NOTIFIED AND ISSUED SPILL # 1602497 TO THIS INCIDENT.     THERE WAS NO FAILURE OF ANY MECHANICAL COMPONENT ON THE TRAILER. THE PRESSURE RELIEVE VENT ON THE DOME COVER RELEASED AS IT SHOULD WHEN THE PRESSURE WAS MOMENTARILY EXCEEDED, AND CLOSED AS THE PRESSURE WAS REDUCED WHEN THE PUMP SHUT DOWN.
column169: ADDITIONAL TRAINING ON THE NEW LOADING SOFTWARE AT THE TERMINAL MAY HAVE HELPED AVOID THIS INCIDENT.

column168: THE DISCHARGE HOSE WAS LEAKING AT GASKET AND FITTING. DRIVER SHUT DOWN PUMPING PROCESS. column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: At 12:55 pm we had a trailer leaving the Phoenix PS yard with 93% sulfuric acid when the BOS noticed the trailer leaking something from the trailer. BOS immediately called the driver to slowly bring the load back to the PS plant.  The trailer dripped 93% sulfuric acid out of the yard and some onto the city street 27th ave at the light where the load was waiting for the light to change. Less than half a gallon was released from the trailer. The drips in the yard were neutralized and the spot on the city street was mostly dry and absorbed by the asphalt. After further investigation the manway gasket was not seated completely on the dome lid causing liquid to seep out into the crow’s nest to the drain pipes and then to the ground. The loader said he did close and tighten the dome lid but did not notice the unseated gasket.  The driver said he did check the wing nut before he left the yard and that they we tight. The gasket was properly put back into place, tightened with no further issues. The load was delivered.

column42: POLYMERIC BEADS, EXPANDABLE, EVOLVING FLAMMABLE VAPOR
column168: AT 19:51 ON 6/18/16 A KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN TRAIN OPERATING ON UNION PACIFIC (UP) TRACK AND WITH A UP CREW STRUCK AN EXCAVATOR TRUCK AT MP 25 ON THE UP GIDDINGS SUBDIVISION. THREE LOCOMOTIVES, NINE RAILCARS, FIFTEEN INTERMODAL WELLS, AND TWENTY NINE CONTAINERS WERE INVOLVED IN THE DERAILMENT. OF THE CARS AND CONTAINERS INVOLVED IN THE DERAILMENT ONLY TWO (INTERMODAL CONTAINERS) WERE LOADED WITH A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL (POLYMERIC BEADS). DURING THE INITIAL ACCIDENT NONE OF THE INTERMODAL CONTAINERS CARRYING HAZMAT BREACHED, HOWEVER WHILE BEING MOVED TO A STAGING LOCATION BY SIDE BOOMS, SNLU 993080 BREACHED RESULTING IN A RELEASE OF 200 POUNDS OF POLYMERIC BEADS FROM ONE OF THE SUPER SACKS INSIDE THE CONTAINERS WHICH HAD BECOME DAMAGED. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANUP AND THE REST OF THE SUPER SACKS WERE TRANSFERRED FOR CONTINUED TRANSPORTATION.
column169: THIS INCIDENT IS CURRENTLY UNDER INVESTIGATION.

column168: Approximately 6 oz. of UN3260 "Preposite Etch 748" released from a 44 lb. paper bag that was torn by the trailer wall. A contractor cleaned the release and over packed the damaged bag. All waste was containerized for disposal.

GATX 206056 was noted by an FRA inspector to be "hissing" from the vacuum relief valve.  Original shipper seal was intact upon discovery. Upon inspection by BNSF HazMat manager, car was not actively hissing, but any slight movement of the vacuum relief valve resulted in a hissing release. The defective vacuum relief valve was removed and replaced with a plug. No other defects were noted with the car.    Shipper is in the process of acquiring an OTMA-3 for movement to destination.
column169: Shipper must ensure that all components are inspected and worthy of containing product inside tank car.  Improved procedures for inspecting components during each loading should be a priority.

column168: TILX 301074 (Residue) was discovered by BNSF employees leaking Propane vapor from the protective housing while awaiting shipment on the Departure 2 track at the Northtown Yard, Minneapolis, MN. The protective housing was found to be unsecured without a shipping seal and the liquid valve plug was loose and leaking propane.  The valve was cycled with the plug secured and checked to make sure the leak stopped.  Once the leak was stopped, the remaining fittings in the housing were checked and the vapor plug and sample port plugs were found to be loose. Those plugs were secured and the car was released to destination with BNSF seal#540257.
column169: The shipper should review the DOT Package securement guidelines and re-train their loading/unloading personnel to prevent future product leaks.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHITE AT THE SLAY TRANSPORTATION CO., INC. FACILITY A LEAK WAS DISCOVERED COMING FROM THE TANKER. AN ESTIMATED 1-GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. SLAY TRANSPORTATION CO., INC. SECURED THE AREA. SWS ENVIRONMENTAL WAS DISPATCHED TO COMPLETE THE CLEANUP AND ASSIST WITH PRODUCT TRANSFER. SWS ENVIRONMENTAL ARRIVED AND INSPECTED SITE. SWS ENVIRONMENTAL DEPLOYED ABSORBENT MATERIAL AS NEEDED. THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED FROM THE LEAKING TANKER INTO A RESCUE TANKER PROVIDED BY SLAY TRANSPORTATION CO, INC. SWS ENVIRONMENTAL RECOVERED THE SPENT ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED INTO ONE (1) 55-GALLON DRUM FOR DISPOSAL. SWS ENVIRONMENTAL WILL COORDINATE DISPOSAL OF THE WASTE GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT,
column169: SINCE THE RELEASE WAS ACCIDENTAL, NO PLANS CURRENTLY EXIST TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. HOWEVER, SLAY TRANSPORTATION CO., INC. WILL CONTINUE TO REINFORCE SAFETY GUIDELINES AND HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ALL PERSONNEL.

EVENT/ CLAIM #60868-1                                                                                                      OUR DRIVER NOTICED THE RELEASE WHEN INSPECTING THE CTMV BEFORE TAKING A BREAK AT A TRUCK STOP. HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS SLOWLY DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CTMV JACKET. THE CTMV SHOWED NO EVIDENCE OF A RELEASE WHEN HE INSPECTED IT PRE-TRIP AT THE SHIPPER. OUR DRIVER PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE DRIP AND CLEANED UP THE IMPACTED PARKING LOT. THE CTMV WAS RELOCATED TO A NEARBY QUALITY CARRIERS TERMINAL WHERE THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS TRANS-LOADED TO ANOTHER CTMV. SHOP INSPECTION REVEALED A 2 INCH LONG CRACK AT THE REAR OF THE TANK BARREL JUST ABOVE THE REAR AXLES.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED

column168: THE DRIVER PULLED OVER AT THE LOVES TRAVEL PLAZA FOR A BREAK AND NOTICED GREEN LIQUID DRIPPING OUT FROM UNDER THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER CALLED DISPATCH FOR ASSISTANCE. DISPATCH CONTRACTED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT WHO MOBILIZED A CREW TO THE SITE FOR A THOROUGH INVESTIGATION. THE CLEANUP CREW ENVIRONMENTAL RESTORATION LLC ARRIVED ONSITE AND PERFORMED AN INSPECTION. BASED ON THE INSPECTION THE CREW DISCOVERED A LOAD SHIFT IN THE TRAILER. AS A RESULT OF THE LOAD SHIFT, A LOSE PALLET HAD SHIFTED FORWARD INTO A DRUM OF MUNSELL GREEN RESIN. THE PALLET POKED A HOLE IN THE SIDE OF THE DRUM AND REMAINED IN THE DRUM SLOWING THE LEAK. THE CREW REMOVED THE PALLET AND PLACED A METAL PUDDY IN THE HOLE TO STOP THE LEAK. AN ESTIMATED 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT HAD BEEN RELEASED ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. THE CREW UNLOADED THE TRAILER UP THE DRUM EACH PIECE OF CARGO WAS WIPED CLEANED AND PLACED ON POLY SHEETING. THE CREW REMOVED DRUM AND PLACED IT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. THE CREW CLEANUP THE TRAILER FLOOR AND RE-LOADED THE CARGO BACK INTO THE TRAILER. AS THE CREW FINISHED THE RE-LOADING THEY TOOK SPECIAL PRECAUTIONS TO ENSURE THE LOAD WAS PROPERLY BLACKED AND BRACED. NO FURTHER ACTION IS REQUIRED.
column169: ENSURE PROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING PRIOR TO SHIPMENT OF FREIGHT LEAKING THE DOCK.

column168: In the accident that occurred on 06/20/2016, JOSHUA DUGAN, driver for TD Petroleum was traveling north east on State Route 62 just outside of Utica, Ohio.  A car traveling toward him was drifting across the center line.  Upon seeing this, the driver moved the tractor trailer as far onto the berm as possible to avoid collision.  The other vehicle continued into the oncoming traffic lane and collided with the semi and tanker.  This forced the truck into the ditch and up an embankment, then to roll back onto the drivers side.  The driver immediately contacted the owner at the home office which is just approximately 10 miles up the road.  A second truck and trailer were dispatched to the scene.  Jae's Towing, of Newark, Ohio was called in to upright and tow the vehicles.  Due to the heat, fuel in compartment 1 and 5 started to mist at the manhole covers.  Diapers were placed under the tanker to catch any spray.  When the truck was overturned, owner, Todd Dugan ground the tankers and immediately started transferring the product to the second tanker, thus alleviating the risk of loss.  The clean up was minimal, the diapers were removed by TD Petroleum, and there was no kill from the small leak.  Although the report was 100 gallon loss, we do not feel that this is accurate, it would have required much more clean up if that were true.  Ohio EPA On Scene Coordinator, Trevor Irwin was on site, and inspected the site after clean up, and was satisfied.
column169: Our drivers receive monthly safety training, along with annual training.  As the accident was not the fault of our driver, and he did everything he could to avoid it, there doesn't seem to be a course of action to prevent further incidents.  We will however continue safety training.

column168: Driver had completed setting up for unloading product at WLSSD Facility, began airing up transport. While pressurizing tank noticed product escaping from crow nest drain tube on top of transport, driver immediately stopping air flow and began to bled off pressure in tank. When product flow stopped approx 1-2 minutes driver and WLSSD personnel began containment/ recovery/ clean up.Inspection of transport plumbing indicated a lower flange gasket (pressure side) on butterfly valve on dipper tube assembly had failed.Clean up and recovery: puddled material was captured/recovered via vacuum pump, wet areas treated with day based absorbent material and recovered, area was rinsed with fresh water thoroughly diluting product to acceptable levels, rinse water recovered. Rinse water, Haz-mat material, and absorbent materials recovered and disposed.
column169: In addition to the annual inspection, the plumbing/fixture flange bolts will be subject to additional inspection checking for proper tightness and signs of leakage.

column168: AS THE DRIVER WAS TRAVELING DOWN FANNIN ROAD, A 2'' LINE COMING FROM THE PRODUCT PUMP VISIBLY CAME LOOSE, CAUSING A RELEASE OF 60 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL.

column168: DRIVER/UNIT DROPPED OFF LEFT EDGE OFF ROAD AND ATTEMPTED TO RECOVER. ONCE AGAINST THE GUARDRAIL, UNABLE TO GET OFF AND UNIT TRIPPED OVER THE GUARDRAIL. DURING THE ROLL-OVER, THE AIR INLET IN THE SPILL BOX WAS BUMPED OPEN SLIGHTLY. LESS THAN 1 QT OF PRODUCT DRIPPED FROM THE INLET. RESPONSE PERSONNEL CLOSED THE INLET VALVE. DRIP AREA WAS SHOVELED UP AND DISPOSED OF BY THIRD PARTY RESPONSE PERSONNEL WHO WAS HANDLED CLEANUP OF ACCIDENT SCENE AS WELL AS REMEDIAL CLEANUP. PRODUCT IN THE TRAILER WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRAILER, AND THEN DAMAGED TRAILER WAS UPRIGHTED FOR RECOVERY.
column169: DRIVER ERROR WAS THE CAUSE OF THE ACCIDENT. ADDITIONAL TRAINING TRAINING WAS PROVIDED COMPANY WIDE ON DEFENSIVE DRIVING AND ACCIDENT PREVENTION TO INCLUDE FATIGUE AND ROLLOVER PREVENTION.

column168: WHEN UNLOADING THE TRAILER, AN EMPLOYEE NOTICED A SLOW LEAK IN A 55 GALLON DRUM. THE INTEGRITY OF THE DRUM APPEARED TO BE COMPROMISED. AFTER DISCOVERING THE DRUM, THE EMPLOYEE AND ANOTHER CO-WORKER TIPPED THE DRUM ON IT'S SIDE TO PREVENT ANY EXCESS MATERIAL FROM LEAKING OUT. THE DRUM WAS OVER PACKED USING A FORKLIFT. UPON INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE FORK LIFT DRIVER HAD HIT THE DRUM WITH A PARROT BEAK THUS DENTING THE DRUM ABOUT 4 INCHES INWARD. THE CORNER OF THE DENT IS WHERE THE SLOW LEAK HAD ORIGINATED. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ABOUT 2 LITERS OF MATERIAL HAD SPILLED INTO THE TRAILER, HOWEVER, IT HAD NOT EXITED THE TRAILER. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT AND PACKED INTO A DRUM.
column169: IT WOULD BE BENEFICIAL FOR ADDITIONAL TRAINING TO BE GIVEN TO FORK LIFT OPERATORS. IT IS IMPORTANT TO BE PROFICIENT WITH SUCH A DANGEROUS PIECE OF EQUIPMENT. IT IS ALSO GOOD PRACTICE TO TAKE YOUR TIME WHILE LOADING AND UNLOADING FREIGHT, ESPECIALLY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS

column168: PLEASE REFER TO ATTACHED SUMMARY  *FAILURE CAUSE #510 WAS DETERMINED TO BE DUE TO VIBRATION OVER TIME.  *FAILURE CAUSE #535 WAS DUE TO THE CABLE/LINKAGE FOR THE VAPOR VALVE AND NOT THE ACTUAL VALVE    AT APPROXIMATELY 9:45 PM ON JUNE 2, 2016, ENROUTE TO PORT NECHES, THE HENIFF TRANSPORTATION DRIVER WAS STOPPED BY A PINELAND, TEXAS STATE TROOPER FOR SPEEDING AND THE TROOPER OBSERVED THE PRESENCE OF SULFUR DIOXIDE ODOR WHILE WALKING ALONG THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER. LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONDERS OF PINELAND/JASPR AND CALABRIAN PERSONNEL WERE CONTACTED TO ESTABLISH AND IMPLEMENT THE APPROPRIATE ACTION NECESSARY TO PREVENT ANY HARM TO THE PUBLIC. THE RESPONDERS MADE THE PRECAUTIONARY DECISION TO EVACUATE LOCALS AROUND A 2 MILE RADIUS AND RESTRICT TRAFFIC FLOW WHILE TRYING TO ESTABLISH THE SOURCE AND MAGNITUDE OF THE LEAK. CALABRIAN’S REPRESENTATIVES ARRIVED ON THE SCENE APPROXIMATELY 11:00 PM AND WERE NOT ALLOWED TO APPROACH THE TRAILER UNTIL 01:30 AM. IT WAS EVENTUALLY AGREED THAT THE GAS LEAK WAS SMALL ENOUGH TO AUTHORIZE RELEASE OF TRAILER TO RETURN TO CALABRIAN’S, PORT NECHES FACILITY AT APPROXIMATELY 03:30 AM.     THE TRAILER WAS RECEIVED BACK AT THE CALABRIAN PLANT SITE AT 04:38 AM AND THE SULFUR DIOXIDE LIQUID WAS THE SAME AS THE ORIGINALLY SHIPPED LEVEL. THIS CONFIRMS THAT NO APPRECIABLE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED TO THE ENVIRONMENT. INSPECTION DISCLOSED A HAIRLINE CRACK ON THE WELD OF A THREADED FITTING CONNECTED TO THE INTERNAL VAPOR VALVE. IT WAS ALSO ESTABLISHED THAT THE INTERNAL VAPOR VALVE WAS NOT SEATING PROPERLY. THE LEAK WAS INTERMITTENT VAPOR FROM THE VAPOR SPACE THROUGH THE CRACK AS A RESULT OF DEFECTIVE INTERNAL VAPOR VALVE WHICH ESSENTIALLY EXPLAINS THE UNCHANGED LIQUID LEVEL.    DOCUMENTED DOT INSPECTIONS CONDUCTED ON SUBJECT TRAILER # 6 BY POLAR ON 04/15/2014 AND 04/02/2015 DID NOT DETECT ANY LEAKS OR VALVE FAILURES. STANDARD INSPECTION CONDUCTED ON ALL OUT BOUND TRAILERS BY CALABRIAN’S OPERATOR AND HENIFF’S DRIVER DID NOT DETECT ANY LEAKS ON TRAILER # 6 BEFORE SHIPMENT ON 06/01/2016.     THE CORRECTIVE ACTION RESULTING FROM ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION CONDUCTED BY CALABRIAN’S TEAM REQUIRING REPLACEMENT OF INTERNAL VALVE AND THE THREADED FITTING WITH A STANDARD NON-THREADED TYPE TO IMPROVE WELD INTEGRITY WAS COMPLETED.
column169: CORRECTIVE ACTIONS WERE COMPLETED.  -THREADED FITTING WAS REPLACED WITH A NON-THREADED TYPE TO ACCOMMODATE A SOCKET WELD WHICH ESSENTIALLY IS AN IMPROVEMENT TO ORIGINAL DESIGN.

column168: DRIVER DIDN'T CHECK TO SEE IF THE TANK WOULD HOLD THE FUEL DELIVERY.
column169: TOOK TANK OUT OF SERVICE.

column168: JEROME H. RHOADS, INC. IS A DISTRIBUTOR OF PRIMARILY RETAIL ENERGY PRODUCTS. ON JUNE 3, 2016 AT 1500 HOURS OUR TANK WAGON DELIVERY DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY OF NO.2 FUEL OIL TO A CUSTOMER'S TANK LOCATED INSIDE THE CUSTOMER'S BUILDING AND OUT OF VIEW TO THE DRIVER. THE DRIVER CONNECTED THE HOSE TO THE FILL PIPE AND COULD HEAR A FAINT WHISTLE WHILE MAKING THE DELIVERY. A WHISTLE WOULD INDICATE THAT THE TANK STILL CONTAINS AIR, AND THEREFORE IS NOT FULL. WHEN THE WHISTLE STOPS, IT MEANS THE TANK IS FULL AND THE DRIVER RELEASES THE HANDLE OF THE HOSE TO STOP THE DELIVERY.     BECAUSE THE WHISTLE WAS FAINT, OUR DRIVER COULD NOT HEAR WHEN IT HAD STOPPED, AND CONTINUED HIS DELIVERY OVERFILLING THE TANK. WHEN THE DRIVER SAW THE NO.2 FUEL OIL SEEPING OUT FROM UNDER THE DOOR TO THE BUILDING, HE IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE DELIVERY AND CALLED THE CUSTOMER TO COME TO THE DELIVERY SITE. WHEN THE CUSTOMER OPENED THE DOOR TO THE BUILDING, OIL THAT HAD GATHERED BEHIND THE DOOR RAN OUT INTO THE ALLEY. THE OVERFLOW OF NO. 2 FUEL OIL SPILLED OUT OF THE VENT PIPE ON TOP OF THE TANK, ONTO THE GROUND AND RAN DOWN A SMALL ALLEY WAY.     ENVIRONMENTAL RECOVERY CORPORATION, AND HAZMAT 2 ENVIRONMENTAL FIRE RESCUE CO. WAS ON SITE, ALONG WITH COMPANY PERSONNEL WHO WORKED TOGETHER TO INSTALL BOOMS AND OIL ABSORBENT MATERIAL, TO CONTAIN AND CLEAN-UP THE SITE. THE LOCAL DEP WAS NOTIFIED ON JUNE 3, 2016.
column169: WE ARE UPGRADING THE VENT PIPING FROM 1" TO 1.5" FROM THE TANK TO THE OUTSIDE, AND CHANGING OUT THE VENT ALARM TANK FILL SIGNAL (WHISTLE) TO ONE THAT RUNS DEEPER INTO THE TANK, WHICH SHOULD IMPROVE THE QUALITY OF THE WHISTLE.     A TANK MONITORING DEVICE WILL ALSO BE ADDED TO THE TANK. THIS WILL ENSURE THAT THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT IN THE TANK WILL BE KNOWN AT ALL TIMES.

column42: ALKYL SULFONIC ACIDS, LIQUID OR ARYL SULFONIC ACIDS, LIQUID WITH NOT MORE THAN 5 PERCENT FREE SULFURIC ACID
column168: On June 17, 2016, a Landstar tractor trailer hauling 48- 55 gallon drums on UN2586 Aryl Sulfonic Acid liquid was involved in a multiple vehicle accident that resulted in a fire and a release of an estimated 50 gallons of material to the trailer floor and adjacent soils. The damaged drums were over packed and staged at the wrecker services yard until disposal could be coordinated.

THE DRIVER WAS MAKING A 90 DEGREE TURN GOING APPROXIMATELY 30 MPH. THE LOAD SHIFTED AS HE MADE THE TURN AND FLIPPED THE TRUCK AND TRAILER ON ITS SIDE. WHEN THE TANKER HIT THE ROAD, THE LOADING HEADS BUSTED. THIS CAUSED THE SPILL. 911 WAS CALLED THE KILGORE POLICE DEPARTMENT CALLED THE KILGORE FIRE CHIEF, WHO IMMEDIATELY STARTED HAZMAT CONTROL. THE DURATION OF THE RELEASE WAS APPROXIMATELY 3 HOURS. THE HAZMAT CREW PLACED HAZMAT SAND BAGS ON EITHER SIDE OF THE SPILL TO CONTAIN IT TO A SMALL AREA. ONCE THE PRODUCT WAS PUMPED OFF THE TANKER, THE ROADWAY WAS CLEANED AND THE SMALL AMOUNT OF CONTAMINATED DIRT WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED.
column169: DRIVERS SHOULD USE CAUTION WHEN MAKING SHARP TURNS ALWAYS BUT ESPECIALLY WHEN LOADED WITH LIQUID.     RECOMMENDATION:   (1) STABILIZING BARS ON EACH SIDE OF THE TANKER COULD BE CONSIDERED.     (2) HIGH IMPACT METAL COULD REPLACE THE METAL ON TANKER LOADING HEADS.

column168: When attempting to fill compartment #3 of the truck, the driver attached the loading arm to the compartment #1 loading head. Compartment # 1 had previously been filled and reach its limited head space. Driver then initiated the fill process and then the diesel camp our of compartment #1 dome.The dome is equipped with a pressure relief devise to prevent over pressurization. So when the wrong compartment was selected by the driver it quickly reached it capacity and since the material was going to the wrong compartment the vent valve was not properly opened, causing the compartment to over pressurize and the material was released.
column169: Addition training was provided and the driver was put on probation.

column168: Due to a braking event during transit, a tote inside the trailer shifted forward. Two totes were strapped in using one tie down but due to the braking force, the tie down broke away from trailer wall. One tote made contact with a skid of pails, causing the side wall of one tote to become compromised. Emergency Response & Training Solutions (ERTS) was immediately contacted to coordinate with a local contractor who was sent out to the location of the release. Neutralizer and absorbent material were used to mitigate the released material. The released material was transferred into overpack containers for later disposal. Due to the hazard of the material, the package specifications were not able to be obtained.
column169: A more sufficient use of blocking and bracing methods may have prevented this release or loading the packages in the nose of trailer and then strapped in. This particular incident has been used in employee training meetings as an example of the importance of proper blocking and bracing during transportation.

column168: THE DRIVER COMPLETED THE TRANSFER OF A WASTE HYDROCHLORIC ACID SOLUTION FROM THE CUSTOMER'S ON-SITE STORAGE TANKS TO THE ENVIRITE OF PENNSYLVANIA TANKER TRUCK. UPON COMPLETION OF PAPERWORK, THE TRUCK WAS CLEARED TO LEAVE THE SITE. UPON MAKING A STOP AT A STOPLIGHT THE DRIVER NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE TANKER. UPON DISCOVERY, THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PULLED ON THE PARKING BRAKE, ENGAGED THE FOUR WAY HAZARD LIGHTS AND CONTACTED THE EMERGENCY COORDINATOR. THE DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE AND BLOCK ANY NEARBY STORM DRAINS WITH THE SUPPLIES FROM THE SPILL KIT ATTACHED TO THE CARGO TANK. THE DRIVER INVESTIGATED THE SOURCE OF RELEASE AND DETERMINED THE FRONT HATCH WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED. HE PROPERLY CLOSED AND SEALED THE FRONT HATCH AND PREVENTED ANY FURTHER LEAKS. PLEASE SEE THE ATTACHED INTERNAL COMPANY SPILL OR RELEASE REPORT AND NOTIFICATION FORM AND DOCUMENTATION FOR ADDITIONAL DETAILS.
column169: HUMAN ERROR WAS DETERMINED TO BE THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT. ADDITIONAL COMMUNICATION TO DRIVERS REGARDING INSPECTION OF ALL SEALS PRIOR TO CLOSING THE CARGO TANKER HATCHES HAS BEEN COMPLETED.

column43: DYED RED LOW SULFUR DIESEL FUEL
column168: STEVE BEYER LOADED HIS GASOLINE TRANSPORT AT MAGELLAN PIPELINE, PLEASANT HILL, IA AND CLOCKED OUT AT 7:30 AM ON 6-17-16. HE LEFT THE PIPELINE AND PROCEEDED ON TO US 65 & IA 5 BYPASS AROUND THE EAST AND SOUTH SIDE OF DES MOINES, IA METROPOLITAN AREA. STEVE WAS TRAVELING WEST BETWEEN THE MILE MARKER/EXIT # 101 AND 102. AT THE UNDERPASS OF SW 88TH / S. 22ND STREET, DES MOINES & WEST DES MOINES, IA. TRAVELING IN THE RIGHT LANE OF THE WEST BOUND SIDE OF THE 4 LANE BYPASS WHEN A RED CHEVY HHR CUT FROM THE LEFT INSIDE LANE TO THE RIGHT LANE. PER MADILYN KAYE ALLERS’ (THE DRIVER OF THE RED CHEVY HHR) STATEMENT TO THE IA STATE PATROL OFFICER K VEON, BADGE # 237, “SHE CUT INTO THE RIGHT LANE IN FRONT OF STEVE SO AS TO NOT REAR END THE CAR AHEAD OF HER.” HER VEHICLE MADE CONTACT WITH STEVE’S FRONT BUMPER AND LEFT FRONT STEER TIRE. PER OUR DRIVERS’ ACCOUNT - “THE STEERING WHEEL JUST SPUN OUT OF MY HAND AND VEERED LEFT TOWARD THE MEDIAN AND THE TRUCK AND TRAILER TIPPED OVER HITTING THE GROUND VERY HARD ON THE RIGHT SIDE. THE TRAILER HIT HARD ENOUGH TO FLATTEN THE SIDE OF THE CARGO TANK 3 FEET WIDE AND THE FULL LENGTH OF THE TRAILER (SEE THE ATTACHED PHOTOS). IT THEN SKIDDED FROM THE RIGHT TO LEFT AND TURNED 180 DEGREES ENDING UP FACING BACK EAST WITH THE TANK SHELL JUST OFF THE INSIDE SHOULDER OF THE ROADWAY IN THE MEDIAN, LEAVING THE FLATTENED SIDE OF THE CARGO TANK DOWN. THERE WERE SIGNS OF FUEL IN THE BOTTOM OF THE MEDIAN AND AT A MANWAYS AND RELIEF VALVES WERE DRY. THERE WERE SIGNS OF FUEL IN THE BOTTOM OF THE MEDIAN AND AT A CULVERT APPROXIMATELY 70 TO 100 FOOT AWAY WHERE IT POOLED AND HAD SORBENT BOOMS IN PLACE.     STEVE BEYER, OUR DRIVER, WAS TAKEN BY AMBULANCE TO THE HOSPITAL WITH A CUT LIP, A CUT ON THE FOREHEAD AND A BROKEN HIP (BROKEN AT THE BALL OF THE FEMUR). STEVE HAD HIP SURGERY ON SATURDAY, 6/18/16 AND RELEASED FOR HOME ON 06/20/2016.     THE DRIVER OF THE CHEVY HHR WAS NOT INJURED. HER VEHICLE WAS DRIVEN OUT OF THE DITCH AND ON TO THE HIGHWAY UNDER ITS OWN POWER AND WAS DRIVEN APPROXIMATELY ¼ OF A MILE TO A WAITING RECOVERY TRUCK TO HAUL IT AWAY.     AT APPROXIMATELY 8:15AM ON FRIDAY JUNE 17, 2016, I, BRENT VANDER LEEST WAS NOTIFIED THAT THE PETROLEUM DISPATCH HAD RECEIVED A PHONE CALL FROM A WOMAN (NO NAME OR LOCATION GIVEN) THAT OUR DRIVER, STEVE BEYER HAD ROLLED HIS GASOLINE TRANSPORT ON IOWA STATE HIGHWAY 5 BYPASS ON THE SOUTH SIDE OF DES MOINES, IA.     I STARTED CALLING DES MOINES POLICE, POLK COUNTY SHERRIFF, WEST DES MOINES POLICE AND DES MOINES HAZMAT RESPONSE UNITS TO REPORT THE ACCIDENT. TO GET A BETTER IDEA OF THE LOCATION, AT THE SAME TIME, I HAD DISPATCH SEND AN EMPTY GAS TRANSPORT TO LOCATE THE WRECK AND REPORT BACK AN EXACT LOCATION. ALSO WHILE THE ENTIRE PRIOR WAS HAPPENING; SULLY SHOP LOADED UP THE PUMP OUT EQUIPMENT, BOOMS AND SORBENT PADS AND WENT TO THE ACCIDENT SITE.     BY 9:30AM SULLY’S TEAM WAS ON SITE AND WAITING FOR PERMISSION TO GO ON SITE TO LOOK AT HOW TO PUMP OUT THE CARGO TANK.     AT 11:30 WE WERE ALLOWED TO
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: DRIVER ALLOWED TRAILER TO FLOAT ACROSS CENTER LINE AT TAIL END WHERE THE UPPER SIDE OF TANKER STRUCK THE TAIL OF A DUMP TRUCK CAUSING ABOUT A 8-INCH GAP INTO THE TANKER ALLOWING FOR APPROX. 870 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL TO SPILL ON HIGHWAY. NO INJURIES, NO OTHER VEHICLES INVOLVED. REMAINING FUEL IN TANKER HAD TO BE PUMPED OUT OF THE COMPARTMENT THAT HAD BEEN DAMAGED. SWS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE CREWS WERE DISPATCHED IMMEDIATELY AND CONTAINED SPILLED FUEL AND DID THE NECESSARY CLEAN-UP AND DISPOSAL OF CLEANUP MATERIALS. THEIR CONTRACT NUMBER WAS 346097-3. I WILL INCLUDE COPIES OF ALL NECESSARY MATERIALS FOR YOUR REPORT PURPOSES.
column169: DRIVER WAS TERMINATED FOR CAUSE, AND JOINING CREW MEMBERS WERE BRIEFED AS TO THE REASON FOR THE TERMINATION. DRIVER FAILED TO CONTROL HIS VEHICLE AS REQUIRED BY COMPANY POLICY AND ALLOWED HIS DISTRACTED DRIVING TO CAUSE AN EXPENSIVE ACCIDENT THAT WAS AVOIDABLE. HE CAUSED MANY LONG HOURS OF TRAFFIC CONGESTION ON 1-240 IN MEMPHIS THAT NEVER SHOULD OF HAPPENED.

column168: RESPONDED TO A LEAKING PACKAGE IN SMALL SORT. UPON INSPECTION, DISCOVERED (6)-3 OUNCE PLASTIC BOTTLES OF URINE SAMPLES, ONE LEAKING. OUTER PAK SOILED DUE TO LEAK. OUTER PAK MARKED WITH UN3373 BIOLOGICAL SUBSTANCES, CATEGORY B MARKINGS. ALL MERCHANDISE DISCARDED THROUGH MEDICAL WASTE CONTRACTOR. PACKAGE OFFERED USING SHIPPER NUMBER 9E3-96R GENOTOX LABORATORIES 4544 S. LAMAR BLVD. AUSTIN, TX 78745.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: The package was dropped in handling.  Examination of the inner container revealed a ruptured seam which allowed the contents to escape. The leakage was contained.  The undamaged portion of the package was repacked for return to shipper.
